state-fraudster/|title=Real estate fraudster Rick Koerber gets 14 years in prison during raucous hearing on his Ponzi scheme|website=The Salt Lake Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> and restitution of $45 million dollars.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/4615109/640/united-states-v-koerber/|title=#640 in United States v. Koerber (D. Utah, 2:17-cr-00037) \u2013 CourtListener.com|website=CourtListener|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAt arraignment in June 2009, Koerber pleaded not guilty to all charges against him, and a trial was set for September 11, 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705311623/Man-pleads-not-guilty-in-Ponzi-case.html|title=Man pleads not guilty in $100M Ponzi scheme|publisher=[[Deseret News]]|date=2009-06-20|accessdate=2009-10-22}}</ref> In November 2009, U.S. [[Federal prosecutor]]s filed 19 additional charges of fraud against Koerber, including one count of [[mail fraud]], six counts of fraud in the offer and sale of [[securities]], one count of sale of unregistered securities, 10 counts of [[wire fraud]], two counts of [[money laundering]] and two counts of [[tax evasion]], bringing the total of charges filed to 22.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/ci_13757418|title=19 new charges filed in alleged megafraud|publisher=[[Salt Lake Tribune]]|date=2009-11-11|accessdate=2009-11-24}}</ref>\n\nDuring evidentiary hearings a key piece of evidence was thrown out resulting in one charge being dropped because it was based on a draft of a letter to key investors and there was no evidence it was sent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/money/56760327-79/koerber-evidence-judge-prosecutors.html.csp|title=Utah judge tosses evidence in Koerber alleged 'Ponzi' case|publisher=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|date=2013-08-21|accessdate=2014-04-16}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2014, a federal judge set a new trial date to try the remaining 18 charges,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/57745307-78/koerber-estate-real-trial.html.csp|title=Man accused of operating Ponzi scheme gets trial date|publisher=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|date=2014-03-28|accessdate=2014-04-16}}</ref> however Judge [[Clark Waddoups]] dismissed the case on June 19, 2014 due to the government violating Koerber's right to a speedy trial. The case was dismissed 5 years to the day after Koerber's [[arraignment]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/58088867-78/koerber-case-waddoups-prosecutors.html.csp|title=Giant Utah fraud case will be dismissed|publisher=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|date=2014-06-19|accessdate=2014-06-20}}</ref> The case was dismissed [[with prejudice]].<ref>http://www.sltrib.com/csp/mediapool/sites/qanews/news/1465245-155/koerber-case-attorney-federal-prosecutors-utah.csp</ref> In December 2014 prosecutors said they were willing to appeal the verdict.<ref>http://www.sltrib.com/news/1913290-155/prosecutors-want-to-refile-utah-fraud</ref>  Prosecutors appealed to the 10th Circuit Court of Appeal in Denver, Colorado.  On January 21, 2016, the court found that Waddoups failed to consider the seriousness of the charges and Koerber's contributions in delaying the trial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865645920/Appeals-courts-sends-case-against-Rick-Koerber-back-to-judge-who-dismissed-it.html|title=Appeals courts sends case against Rick Koerber back to judge who dismissed it|last=Romboy|first=Dennis|date=2016-01-21|newspaper=DeseretNews.com|access-date=2017-02-10|language=en}}</ref>  The case was sent back to the lower court and Waddoups recused himself from reviewing it.  On August 25, 2016, federal judge [[Jill Parrish]] ruled that the charges could be reinstated.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865645920/Appeals-courts-sends-case-against-Rick-Koerber-back-to-judge-who-dismissed-it.html|title=Appeals courts sends case against Rick Koerber back to judge who dismissed it|last=Romboy|first=Dennis|date=2016-01-21|newspaper=DeseretNews.com|access-date=2017-02-10|language=en}}</ref> Koerber was again indicted by a grand jury on January 18, 2017, on 18 charges,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/4836244-155/ex-utah-county-real-estate-guru-koerber|title=Utah's 'free capitalist' Koerber faces reindictment over Ponzi scheme|last=Tribune|first=Tom Harvey  The Salt Lake|newspaper=The Salt Lake Tribune|access-date=2017-02-10|language=en-US}}</ref> however, the jury deadlocked and a mistrial was declared on October 16, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/2017/10/16/20635179/jury-deadlocked-in-fraud-trial-for-utah-businessman-rick-koerber|title=Jury deadlocked in fraud trial for Utah businessman Rick Koerber|last=Romero|first=McKenzie|date=2017-10-16|website=Deseret News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, 2017, the United States Attorney's Office (District of Utah) announced plans to retry the case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-ut/pr/statement-us-v-koerber|title=Statement on U.S. v Koerber|date=2017-11-01|website=www.justice.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>  Filmmaker [[Richard Dutcher]] testified about Koerber's $5 million funding of the 2009 erotic horror film ''[[Evil Angel (film)|Evil Angel]]'' while several of Koeber's investors testified they did not know or approve of their money to bankroll a film, which prosecutors characterized as characteristic of Koerber's dishonest practices.<ref name=Harvey2017>Tom Harvey (2017-09-12). [https://www.sltrib.com/news/business/2017/09/12/accused-real-estate-guru-invested-in-sexy-horror-flick-to-raise-funds-for-movie-on-mormon-church-founder-joseph-smith/ Accused real estate guru invested in sexy horror flick to raise funds for movie on Mormon church founder Joseph Smith] The Salt Lake Tribue,  accessed 13 April 2020</ref> On September 20, 2018, a federal jury in the District of Utah convicted Claud R. (\u201cRick\u201d) Koerber on charges of Fraud in the Offer or Sale of Securities, Wire Fraud, and Money Laundering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-ut/us-v-koerber|title=US v. Koerber|date=2019-03-13|website=www.justice.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>  On October 15, 2019, Judge [[Frederic Block]] sentenced Koerber to 170 months (14 years, 2 months) in federal prison<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> and restitution of $45 million dollars.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n== Criminal Conviction ==\n\"Jury of eight men and four women found Koerber guilty of 15 counts of securities fraud, wire fraud and money laundering. They found him not guilty on two counts of tax evasion.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fox13now.com/2018/09/20/jury-finds-free-capitalist-rick-koerber-guilty-in-one-of-utahs-biggest-fraud-cases/|title=Jury finds \u2018Free Capitalist\u2019 Rick Koerber guilty in one of Utah\u2019s biggest fraud cases|date=2018-09-21|work=fox13now.com|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nKoerber was sentenced to 170 months (14 years, 2 months) in federal prison<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> and restitution of $45 million dollars.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.blogtalkradio.com/freecapitalist FreeCapitalist Radio with Rick Koerber]\n* [http://freecapitalist.com/ FreeCapitalist Project]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koerber, Rick}}\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Utah]]\n[[Category:American radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Pyramid and Ponzi schemes]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Casper, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Utah]]\n", "name_user": "ChristensenMJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rick_Koerber"}
